[32m│[0m 1. **JavaScript injection** (`");alert('XSS');//`) attempted to break out of [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m the string context by closing the quote. While it technically executed (the  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m alert would fire), the application detected this pattern and flagged it as   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m malicious.                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. **HTML tag injections** (`<img>` and `<svg>`) bypassed the JavaScript     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m string context entirely. When `document.write()` rendered the content        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m containing these HTML tags, they created new DOM elements that executed the  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m XSS payload through event handlers (`onerror`, `onload`).                    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Evidence of Actual Execution:**                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - The flag only appears when XSS is successfully executed                    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Success is indicated by `success_circle.png` image                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Failed attempts show `error_circle.png` with "Failed! Try again!"          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ---                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
